  "text": "A modified approach with respect to the method proposed by Ugander et al. [CITATION_1] has been adopted to measure PTT. The heart is a pulsatile pump and with every heartbeat RV ejects in the pulmonary circulation an amount of blood equal to the anterograde RVSV. Hence, PTT may be measured as the number of cardiac cycles, or pulmonary transit beats (PTB), required for a bolus of contrast agent to pass from the RV to the left atrium. The gadolinium first-pass perfusion imaging allows us to obtain an image for each heartbeat for 60 consecutive beats and it may be used to measure the PTT. Briefly, in the horizontal long-axis view of first pass imaging, a region of interest was placed in the RV cavity and copied in the same position for the entire stack of images. The average signal intensity (SI) of the region of interest was measured in every images and a SI/heartbeat curve was generated ( Figure 1A and B). A second SI/heartbeat curve was generated from another region of interest placed in left atrium. The PTT was measured as the peak-to-peak time interval between the curves. PTB was defined by the peak-to-peak number of cardiac cycles between the two curves. In a preliminary study, we compared the measurement of PTT and PTB as onset-to-onset, peak-to-peak and half-width time interval of the wash-in phase of SI/heartbeat curves. In a preliminary evaluation, we found no significant differences among such methods, and we finally chose the peak-to-peak time interval as the most reproducible, yielding intra-class correlation coefficient values of 0.99 and 0.97 for intraobserver and inter-observer reliability, respectively.",
